[[tssid=18950214T0004Z]]

[[uid=830lwfqb]] THIRD ACT
[[uid=830lwfqc]] SCENE
[[uid=830lwfqd]]  [[attitudeInstr]] [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lwfqf]] Morning-room at the Manor House.
[[uid=830lwfqg]] 
[[uid=830lwfqh]] [Gwendolen and Cecily are at the
[[uid=830lwfqj]] window, looking out into the garden.]
[[uid=830lwfqk]] 
[[uid=830lwfql]] GWENDOLEN.
[[uid=830lwfqm]] The fact that they did not follow us at [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwfqn]] once into the house, as any one else
[[uid=830lwfqp]] would have done, seems to me to show
[[uid=830lwfqq]] that they have some sense of shame
[[uid=830lwfqr]] left.
[[uid=830lwfqs]] 
[[uid=830lwfqt]] CECILY.
[[uid=830lwfqw]] They have been eating muffins. That
[[uid=830lwfqx]] looks like repentance.
[[uid=830lwfqy]] 
[[uid=830lwfqz]] GWENDOLEN.
[[uid=830lwfr0]] [After a pause.] They don’t seem to
[[uid=830lwfr1]] notice us at all. Couldn’t you cough?
[[uid=830lwfr2]] 
[[uid=830lwfr3]] CECILY.
[[uid=830lwfr4]] But I haven’t got a cough.
[[uid=830lwfr5]] 
[[uid=830lwfr6]] GWENDOLEN.
[[uid=830lwfr7]] They’re looking at us. What effrontery!
[[uid=830lwfr8]] 
[[uid=830lwfr9]] CECILY.
[[uid=830lwfrb]] They’re approaching. That’s very
[[uid=830lwfrc]] forward of them.
[[uid=830lwfrd]] 
[[uid=830lwfrf]] GWENDOLEN.
[[uid=830lwfrg]] Let us preserve a dignified silence.
[[uid=830lwfrh]]  [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwfrj]] CECILY.
[[uid=830lwfrk]] Certainly. It’s the only thing to do
[[uid=830lwfrl]] now. [Enter Jack followed by Algernon.
[[uid=830lwfrm]] They whistle some dreadful popular air
[[uid=830lwfrn]] from a British Opera.]
[[uid=830lwfrp]] 
[[uid=830lwfrq]] GWENDOLEN. [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lwfrr]] This dignified silence seems to produce
[[uid=830lwfrs]] an unpleasant effect.
[[uid=830lwfrt]] 
[[uid=830lwfrw]] CECILY.
[[uid=830lwfrx]] A most distasteful one.
[[uid=830lwfry]] 
[[uid=830lwfrz]] GWENDOLEN.
[[uid=830lwfs0]] But we will not be the first to speak.
[[uid=830lwfs1]] 
[[uid=830lwfs2]] CECILY.
[[uid=830lwfs3]] Certainly not. [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lwfs4]] 
[[uid=830lwfs5]] GWENDOLEN.
[[uid=830lwfs6]] Mr. Worthing, I have something very [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lwfs7]] particular to ask you. Much depends on
[[uid=830lwfs8]] your reply.
[[uid=830lwfs9]]  [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwfsb]] CECILY.
[[uid=830lwfsc]] Gwendolen, your common sense is
[[uid=830lwfsd]] invaluable. Mr. Moncrieff, kindly
[[uid=830lwfsf]] answer me the following question. Why
[[uid=830lwfsg]] did you pretend to be my guardian’s
[[uid=830lwfsh]] brother?
[[uid=830lwfsj]] 
[[uid=830lwfsk]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lwfsl]] In order that I might have an
[[uid=830lwfsm]] opportunity of meeting you.
[[uid=830lwfsn]] 
[[uid=830lwfsp]] CECILY.
[[uid=830lwfsq]] [To Gwendolen.] That certainly seems a
[[uid=830lwfsr]] satisfactory explanation, does it not?
[[uid=830lwfss]] 
[[uid=830lwfst]] GWENDOLEN.
[[uid=830lwfsw]] Yes, dear, if you can believe him.
[[uid=830lwfsx]] 
[[uid=830lwfsy]] CECILY.
[[uid=830lwfsz]] I don’t. But that does not affect the
[[uid=830lwft0]] wonderful beauty of his answer.
[[uid=830lwft1]] 
[[uid=830lwft2]] GWENDOLEN.
[[uid=830lwft3]] True. In matters of grave importance,
[[uid=830lwft4]] style, not sincerity is the vital
[[uid=830lwft5]] thing. Mr. Worthing, what explanation
[[uid=830lwft6]] can you offer to me for pretending to
[[uid=830lwft7]] have a brother? Was it in order that
[[uid=830lwft8]] you might have an opportunity of coming
[[uid=830lwft9]] up to town to see me as often as
[[uid=830lwftb]] possible?
[[uid=830lwftc]] 
[[uid=830lwftd]] JACK. [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lwftf]] Can you doubt it, Miss Fairfax?
[[uid=830lwftg]] 
[[uid=830lwfth]] GWENDOLEN.
[[uid=830lwftj]] I have the gravest doubts upon the
[[uid=830lwftk]] subject. But I intend to crush them.
[[uid=830lwftl]] This is not the moment for German
[[uid=830lwftm]] scepticism. [Moving to Cecily.] Their
[[uid=830lwftn]] explanations appear to be quite
[[uid=830lwftp]] satisfactory, especially Mr.
[[uid=830lwftq]] Worthing’s. That seems to me to have
[[uid=830lwftr]] the stamp of truth upon it.
[[uid=830lwfts]] 
[[uid=830lwftt]] CECILY.
[[uid=830lwftw]] I am more than content with what Mr.
[[uid=830lwftx]] Moncrieff said. His voice alone
[[uid=830lwfty]] inspires one with absolute credulity. [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwftz]] 
[[uid=830lwfw0]] GWENDOLEN.
[[uid=830lwfw1]] Then you think we should forgive them?
[[uid=830lwfw2]] 
[[uid=830lwfw3]] CECILY.
[[uid=830lwfw4]] Yes. I mean no.
[[uid=830lwfw5]] 
[[uid=830lwfw6]] GWENDOLEN.
[[uid=830lwfw7]] True! I had forgotten. There are
[[uid=830lwfw8]] principles at stake that one cannot
[[uid=830lwfw9]] surrender. Which of us should tell
[[uid=830lwfwb]] them? The task is not a pleasant one. [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lwfwc]] 
[[uid=830lwfwd]] CECILY.
[[uid=830lwfwf]] Could we not both speak at the same [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwfwg]] time?
[[uid=830lwfwh]] 
[[uid=830lwfwj]] GWENDOLEN.
[[uid=830lwfwk]] An excellent idea! I nearly always
[[uid=830lwfwl]] speak at the same time as other people.
[[uid=830lwfwm]] Will you take the time from me?
[[uid=830lwfwn]] 
[[uid=830lwfwp]] CECILY.
[[uid=830lwfwq]] Certainly. [Gwendolen beats time with
[[uid=830lwfwr]] uplifted finger.] [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwfws]]  [[attitudeInstr]] [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwfwt]] GWENDOLEN and CECILY [Speaking
[[uid=830lwfww]] together.] Your Christian names are [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwfwx]] still an insuperable barrier. That is
[[uid=830lwfwy]] all!
[[uid=830lwfwz]] 
[[uid=830lwfx0]] JACK and ALGERNON [Speaking together.]
[[uid=830lwfx1]] Our Christian names! Is that all? But
[[uid=830lwfx2]] we are going to be christened this
[[uid=830lwfx3]] afternoon.
[[uid=830lwfx4]] 
[[uid=830lwfx5]] GWENDOLEN.
[[uid=830lwfx6]] [To Jack.] For my sake you are prepared
[[uid=830lwfx7]] to do this terrible thing?
[[uid=830lwfx8]] 
[[uid=830lwfx9]] JACK.
[[uid=830lwfxb]] I am.
[[uid=830lwfxc]] 
[[uid=830lwfxd]] CECILY.
[[uid=830lwfxf]] [To Algernon.] To please me you are
[[uid=830lwfxg]] ready to face this fearful ordeal?
[[uid=830lwfxh]] 
[[uid=830lwfxj]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lwfxk]] I am!
[[uid=830lwfxl]] 
[[uid=830lwfxm]] GWENDOLEN.
[[uid=830lwfxn]] How absurd to talk of the equality of
[[uid=830lwfxp]] the sexes! Where questions of
[[uid=830lwfxq]] self-sacrifice are concerned, men are
[[uid=830lwfxr]] infinitely beyond us.
[[uid=830lwfxs]] 
[[uid=830lwfxt]] JACK.
[[uid=830lwfxw]] We are. [Clasps hands with Algernon.]
[[uid=830lwfxx]] 
[[uid=830lwfxy]] CECILY.
[[uid=830lwfxz]] They have moments of physical courage
[[uid=830lwfy0]] of which we women know absolutely
[[uid=830lwfy1]] nothing.
[[uid=830lwfy2]] 
[[uid=830lwfy3]] GWENDOLEN.
[[uid=830lwfy4]] [To Jack.] Darling!
[[uid=830lwfy5]] 
[[uid=830lwfy6]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lwfy7]] [To Cecily.] Darling! [They fall into
[[uid=830lwfy8]] each other’s arms.]
[[uid=830lwfy9]] 
[[uid=830lwfyb]] [Enter Merriman. When he enters he
[[uid=830lwfyc]] coughs loudly, seeing the situation.]
[[uid=830lwfyd]] 
[[uid=830lwfyf]] MERRIMAN.
[[uid=830lwfyg]] Ahem! Ahem! Lady Bracknell!
[[uid=830lwfyh]] 
[[uid=830lwfyj]] JACK.
[[uid=830lwfyk]] Good heavens!
[[uid=830lwfyl]] 
[[uid=830lwfym]] [Enter Lady Bracknell. The couples
[[uid=830lwfyn]] separate in alarm. Exit Merriman.] [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwfyp]] 
[[uid=830lwfyq]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwfyr]] Gwendolen! What does this mean?
[[uid=830lwfys]] 
[[uid=830lwfyt]] GWENDOLEN.
[[uid=830lwfyw]] Merely that I am engaged to be married
[[uid=830lwfyx]] to Mr. Worthing, mamma. [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwfyy]] 
[[uid=830lwfyz]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwfz0]] Come here. Sit down. Sit down [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwfz1]] immediately. Hesitation of any kind is
[[uid=830lwfz2]] a sign of mental decay in the young, of
[[uid=830lwfz3]] physical weakness in the old. [Turns to
[[uid=830lwfz4]] Jack.] Apprised, sir, of my daughter’s
[[uid=830lwfz5]] sudden flight by her trusty maid, whose
[[uid=830lwfz6]] confidence I purchased by means of a
[[uid=830lwfz7]] small coin, I followed her at once by a
[[uid=830lwfz8]] luggage train. Her unhappy father is, I [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lwfz9]] am glad to say, under the impression [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lwfzb]] that she is attending a more than
[[uid=830lwfzc]] usually lengthy lecture by the
[[uid=830lwfzd]] University Extension Scheme on the
[[uid=830lwfzf]] Influence of a permanent income on
[[uid=830lwfzg]] Thought. I do not propose to undeceive
[[uid=830lwfzh]] him. Indeed I have never undeceived him
[[uid=830lwfzj]] on any question. I would consider it
[[uid=830lwfzk]] wrong. But of course, you will clearly
[[uid=830lwfzl]] understand that all communication
[[uid=830lwfzm]] between yourself and my daughter must
[[uid=830lwfzn]] cease immediately from this moment. On
[[uid=830lwfzp]] this point, as indeed on all points, I
[[uid=830lwfzq]] am firm.
[[uid=830lwfzr]] 
[[uid=830lwfzs]] JACK.
[[uid=830lwfzt]] I am engaged to be married to
[[uid=830lwfzw]] Gwendolen, Lady Bracknell!
[[uid=830lwfzx]] 
[[uid=830lwfzy]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwfzz]] You are nothing of the kind, sir. And
[[uid=830lwg00]] now, as regards Algernon! . . .
[[uid=830lwg01]] Algernon!
[[uid=830lwg02]] 
[[uid=830lwg03]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lwg04]] Yes, Aunt Augusta.
[[uid=830lwg05]] 
[[uid=830lwg06]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwg07]] May I ask if it is in this house that
[[uid=830lwg08]] your invalid friend Mr. Bunbury
[[uid=830lwg09]] resides?
[[uid=830lwg0b]] 
[[uid=830lwg0c]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lwg0d]] [Stammering.] Oh! No! Bunbury doesn’t
[[uid=830lwg0f]] live here. Bunbury is somewhere else at
[[uid=830lwg0g]] present. In fact, Bunbury is dead.
[[uid=830lwg0h]] 
[[uid=830lwg0j]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwg0k]] Dead! When did Mr. Bunbury die? His
[[uid=830lwg0l]] death must have been extremely sudden.
[[uid=830lwg0m]] 
[[uid=830lwg0n]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lwg0p]] [Airily.] Oh! I killed Bunbury this
[[uid=830lwg0q]] afternoon. I mean poor Bunbury died
[[uid=830lwg0r]] this afternoon.
[[uid=830lwg0s]] 
[[uid=830lwg0t]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwg0w]] What did he die of? [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwg0x]] 
[[uid=830lwg0y]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lwg0z]] Bunbury? Oh, he was quite exploded.
[[uid=830lwg10]] 
[[uid=830lwg11]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwg12]] Exploded! Was he the victim of a
[[uid=830lwg13]] revolutionary outrage? I was not aware
[[uid=830lwg14]] that Mr. Bunbury was interested in
[[uid=830lwg15]] social legislation. If so, he is well
[[uid=830lwg16]] punished for his morbidity.
[[uid=830lwg17]] 
[[uid=830lwg18]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lwg19]] My dear Aunt Augusta, I mean he was
[[uid=830lwg1b]] found out! The doctors found out that [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lwg1c]] Bunbury could not live, that is what I
[[uid=830lwg1d]] mean—so Bunbury died.
[[uid=830lwg1f]] 
[[uid=830lwg1g]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwg1h]] He seems to have had great confidence
[[uid=830lwg1j]] in the opinion of his physicians. I am
[[uid=830lwg1k]] glad, however, that he made up his mind
[[uid=830lwg1l]] at the last to some definite course of
[[uid=830lwg1m]] action, and acted under proper medical
[[uid=830lwg1n]] advice. And now that we have finally [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwg1p]] got rid of this Mr. Bunbury, may I ask,
[[uid=830lwg1q]] Mr. Worthing, who is that young person
[[uid=830lwg1r]] whose hand my nephew Algernon is now
[[uid=830lwg1s]] holding in what seems to me a
[[uid=830lwg1t]] peculiarly unnecessary manner?
[[uid=830lwg1w]]  [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwg1x]] JACK.
[[uid=830lwg1y]] That lady is Miss Cecily Cardew, my
[[uid=830lwg1z]] ward. [Lady Bracknell bows coldly to
[[uid=830lwg20]] Cecily.]
[[uid=830lwg21]]  [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lwg22]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lwg23]] I am engaged to be married to Cecily,
[[uid=830lwg24]] Aunt Augusta.
[[uid=830lwg25]] 
[[uid=830lwg26]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwg27]] I beg your pardon?
[[uid=830lwg28]] 
[[uid=830lwg29]] CECILY.
[[uid=830lwg2b]] Mr. Moncrieff and I are engaged to be
[[uid=830lwg2c]] married, Lady Bracknell.
[[uid=830lwg2d]] 
[[uid=830lwg2f]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwg2g]] [With a shiver, crossing to the sofa
[[uid=830lwg2h]] and sitting down.] I do not know
[[uid=830lwg2j]] whether there is anything peculiarly
[[uid=830lwg2k]] exciting in the air of this particular
[[uid=830lwg2l]] part of Hertfordshire, but the number
[[uid=830lwg2m]] of engagements that go on seems to me
[[uid=830lwg2n]] considerably above the proper average
[[uid=830lwg2p]] that statistics have laid down for our
[[uid=830lwg2q]] guidance. I think some preliminary
[[uid=830lwg2r]] inquiry on my part would not be out of
[[uid=830lwg2s]] place. Mr. Worthing, is Miss Cardew at
[[uid=830lwg2t]] all connected with any of the larger
[[uid=830lwg2w]] railway stations in London? I merely [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwg2x]] desire information. Until yesterday I
[[uid=830lwg2y]] had no idea that there were any
[[uid=830lwg2z]] families or persons whose origin was a
[[uid=830lwg30]] Terminus. [Jack looks perfectly
[[uid=830lwg31]] furious, but restrains himself.] [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwg32]] 
[[uid=830lwg33]] JACK.
[[uid=830lwg34]] [In a clear, cold voice.] Miss Cardew
[[uid=830lwg35]] is the grand-daughter of the late Mr.
[[uid=830lwg36]] Thomas Cardew of 149 Belgrave Square,
[[uid=830lwg37]] S.W.; Gervase Park, Dorking, Surrey;
[[uid=830lwg38]] and the Sporran, Fifeshire, N.B.
[[uid=830lwg39]] 
[[uid=830lwg3b]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwg3c]] That sounds not unsatisfactory. Three
[[uid=830lwg3d]] addresses always inspire confidence,
[[uid=830lwg3f]] even in tradesmen. But what proof have
[[uid=830lwg3g]] I of their authenticity?
[[uid=830lwg3h]]  [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwg3j]] JACK.
[[uid=830lwg3k]] I have carefully preserved the Court
[[uid=830lwg3l]] Guides of the period. They are open to
[[uid=830lwg3m]] your inspection, Lady Bracknell.
[[uid=830lwg3n]] 
[[uid=830lwg3p]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwg3q]] [Grimly.] I have known strange errors
[[uid=830lwg3r]] in that publication.
[[uid=830lwg3s]] 
[[uid=830lwg3t]] JACK.
[[uid=830lwg3w]] Miss Cardew’s family solicitors are [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwg3x]] Messrs. Markby, Markby, and Markby.
[[uid=830lwg3y]] 
[[uid=830lwg3z]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwg40]] Markby, Markby, and Markby? A firm of
[[uid=830lwg41]] the very highest position in their
[[uid=830lwg42]] profession. Indeed I am told that one
[[uid=830lwg43]] of the Mr. Markby’s is occasionally to
[[uid=830lwg44]] be seen at dinner parties. So far I am
[[uid=830lwg45]] satisfied.
[[uid=830lwg46]] 
[[uid=830lwg47]] JACK.
[[uid=830lwg48]] [Very irritably.] How extremely kind of
[[uid=830lwg49]] you, Lady Bracknell! I have also in my
[[uid=830lwg4b]] possession, you will be pleased to
[[uid=830lwg4c]] hear, certificates of Miss Cardew’s
[[uid=830lwg4d]] birth, baptism, whooping cough,
[[uid=830lwg4f]] registration, vaccination,
[[uid=830lwg4g]] confirmation, and the measles; both the
[[uid=830lwg4h]] German and the English variety.
[[uid=830lwg4j]] 
[[uid=830lwg4k]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwg4l]] Ah! A life crowded with incident, I
[[uid=830lwg4m]] see; though perhaps somewhat too
[[uid=830lwg4n]] exciting for a young girl. I am not
[[uid=830lwg4p]] myself in favour of premature
[[uid=830lwg4q]] experiences. [Rises, looks at her
[[uid=830lwg4r]] watch.] Gwendolen! the time approaches
[[uid=830lwg4s]] for our departure. We have not a moment
[[uid=830lwg4t]] to lose. As a matter of form, Mr.
[[uid=830lwg4w]] Worthing, I had better ask you if Miss
[[uid=830lwg4x]] Cardew has any little fortune?
[[uid=830lwg4y]] 
[[uid=830lwg4z]] JACK.
[[uid=830lwg50]] Oh! about a hundred and thirty thousand
[[uid=830lwg51]] pounds in the Funds. That is all.
[[uid=830lwg52]] Goodbye, Lady Bracknell. So pleased to
[[uid=830lwg53]] have seen you.
[[uid=830lwg54]] 
[[uid=830lwg55]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwg56]] [Sitting down again.] A moment, Mr.
[[uid=830lwg57]] Worthing. A hundred and thirty thousand [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwg58]] pounds! And in the Funds! Miss Cardew
[[uid=830lwg59]] seems to me a most attractive young
[[uid=830lwg5b]] lady, now that I look at her. Few girls
[[uid=830lwg5c]] of the present day have any really
[[uid=830lwg5d]] solid qualities, any of the qualities
[[uid=830lwg5f]] that last, and improve with time. We
[[uid=830lwg5g]] live, I regret to say, in an age of
[[uid=830lwg5h]] surfaces. [To Cecily.] Come over here,
[[uid=830lwg5j]] dear. [Cecily goes across.] Pretty
[[uid=830lwg5k]] child! your dress is sadly simple, and
[[uid=830lwg5l]] your hair seems almost as Nature might
[[uid=830lwg5m]] have left it. But we can soon alter all
[[uid=830lwg5n]] that. A thoroughly experienced French
[[uid=830lwg5p]] maid produces a really marvellous
[[uid=830lwg5q]] result in a very brief space of time. I
[[uid=830lwg5r]] remember recommending one to young Lady
[[uid=830lwg5s]] Lancing, and after three months her own
[[uid=830lwg5t]] husband did not know her.
[[uid=830lwg5w]] 
[[uid=830lwg5x]] JACK.
[[uid=830lwg5y]] And after six months nobody knew her.
[[uid=830lwg5z]] 
[[uid=830lwg60]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwg61]] [Glares at Jack for a few moments. Then
[[uid=830lwg62]] bends, with a practised smile, to
[[uid=830lwg63]] Cecily.] Kindly turn round, sweet
[[uid=830lwg64]] child. [Cecily turns completely round.]
[[uid=830lwg65]] No, the side view is what I want.
[[uid=830lwg66]] [Cecily presents her profile.] Yes,
[[uid=830lwg67]] quite as I expected. There are distinct
[[uid=830lwg68]] social possibilities in your profile.
[[uid=830lwg69]] The two weak points in our age are its
[[uid=830lwg6b]] want of principle and its want of
[[uid=830lwg6c]] profile. The chin a little higher,
[[uid=830lwg6d]] dear. Style largely depends on the way
[[uid=830lwg6f]] the chin is worn. They are worn very
[[uid=830lwg6g]] high, just at present. Algernon!
[[uid=830lwg6h]]  [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lwg6j]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lwg6k]] Yes, Aunt Augusta!
[[uid=830lwg6l]] 
[[uid=830lwg6m]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwg6n]] There are distinct social possibilities
[[uid=830lwg6p]] in Miss Cardew’s profile.
[[uid=830lwg6q]] 
[[uid=830lwg6r]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lwg6s]] Cecily is the sweetest, dearest,
[[uid=830lwg6t]] prettiest girl in the whole world. And
[[uid=830lwg6w]] I don’t care twopence about social
[[uid=830lwg6x]] possibilities.
[[uid=830lwg6y]] 
[[uid=830lwg6z]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwg70]] Never speak disrespectfully of Society,
[[uid=830lwg71]] Algernon. Only people who can’t get
[[uid=830lwg72]] into it do that. [To Cecily.] Dear
[[uid=830lwg73]] child, of course you know that Algernon
[[uid=830lwg74]] has nothing but his debts to depend
[[uid=830lwg75]] upon. But I do not approve of mercenary
[[uid=830lwg76]] marriages. When I married Lord
[[uid=830lwg77]] Bracknell I had no fortune of any kind.
[[uid=830lwg78]] But I never dreamed for a moment of [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwg79]] allowing that to stand in my way. Well, [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lwg7b]] I suppose I must give my consent.
[[uid=830lwg7c]] 
[[uid=830lwg7d]] ALGERNON.
[[uid=830lwg7f]] Thank you, Aunt Augusta.
[[uid=830lwg7g]] 
[[uid=830lwg7h]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwg7j]] Cecily, you may kiss me!
[[uid=830lwg7k]] 
[[uid=830lwg7l]] CECILY.
[[uid=830lwg7m]] [Kisses her.] Thank you, Lady
[[uid=830lwg7n]] Bracknell.
[[uid=830lwg7p]] 
[[uid=830lwg7q]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwg7r]] You may also address me as Aunt Augusta [[attitudeInstr]]
[[uid=830lwg7s]] for the future.
[[uid=830lwg7t]] 
[[uid=830lwg7w]] CECILY.
[[uid=830lwg7x]] Thank you, Aunt Augusta.
[[uid=830lwg7y]] 
[[uid=830lwg7z]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwg80]] The marriage, I think, had better take
[[uid=830lwg81]] place quite soon.
[[uid=830lwg82]] 
[[uid=830lwg83]] ALGERNON. [[attitudeExp]]
[[uid=830lwg84]] Thank you, Aunt Augusta.
[[uid=830lwg85]] 
[[uid=830lwg86]] CECILY.
[[uid=830lwg87]] Thank you, Aunt Augusta.
[[uid=830lwg88]] 
[[uid=830lwg89]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwg8b]] To speak frankly, I am not in favour of
[[uid=830lwg8c]] long engagements. They give people the
[[uid=830lwg8d]] opportunity of finding out each other’s
[[uid=830lwg8f]] character before marriage, which I
[[uid=830lwg8g]] think is never advisable.
[[uid=830lwg8h]] 
[[uid=830lwg8j]] JACK.
[[uid=830lwg8k]] I beg your pardon for interrupting you,
[[uid=830lwg8l]] Lady Bracknell, but this engagement is
[[uid=830lwg8m]] quite out of the question. I am Miss
[[uid=830lwg8n]] Cardew’s guardian, and she cannot marry
[[uid=830lwg8p]] without my consent until she comes of
[[uid=830lwg8q]] age. That consent I absolutely decline
[[uid=830lwg8r]] to give.
[[uid=830lwg8s]] 
[[uid=830lwg8t]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwg8w]] Upon what grounds may I ask? Algernon
[[uid=830lwg8x]] is an extremely, I may almost say an
[[uid=830lwg8y]] ostentatiously, eligible young man. He
[[uid=830lwg8z]] has nothing, but he looks everything.
[[uid=830lwg90]] What more can one desire?
[[uid=830lwg91]] 
[[uid=830lwg92]] JACK.
[[uid=830lwg93]] It pains me very much to have to speak
[[uid=830lwg94]] frankly to you, Lady Bracknell, about
[[uid=830lwg95]] your nephew, but the fact is that I do
[[uid=830lwg96]] not approve at all of his moral
[[uid=830lwg97]] character. I suspect him of being
[[uid=830lwg98]] untruthful. [Algernon and Cecily look
[[uid=830lwg99]] at him in indignant amazement.]
[[uid=830lwg9b]] 
[[uid=830lwg9c]] LADY BRACKNELL.
[[uid=830lwg9d]] Untruthful! My nephew Algernon?
[[uid=830lwg9f]] Impossible! He is an Oxonian.
[[uid=830lwg9g]] 
[[uid=830lwg9h]] JACK.
[[uid=830lwg9j]] I fear there can be no possible doubt
[[uid=830lwg9k]] about the matter. This afternoon during
[[uid=830lwg9l]] my temporary absence in London on an
[[uid=830lwg9m]] important question of romance, he
[[uid=830lwg9n]] obtained admission to my house by means
[[uid=830lwg9p]] of the false pretence of being my
[[uid=830lwg9q]] brother. Under an assumed name he
[[uid=830lwg9r]] drank, I’ve just been informed by my
[[uid=830lwg9s]] butler, an entire pint bottle of my
[[uid=830lwg9t]] Perrier-Jouet, Brut, ’89; wine I was
